@NODE "Use" "Usage"
@{u}Using KewlCDPro Config Editor@{uu}

   Double click on the icon from Workbench or launch it from the CLI, a GUI
will open followed by a requester asking you if it's OK to load KewlCD.cfg as
a KewlCDPro 2 (if that is found), if your one is not for KewlCDPro 2.0, you
must click cancel Cancel. However, if you have a KewlCDPro 1.6 you can import
that from the menu (more on menus later).

   You can then change each of the items, they all relate to the config items
(I did my best to keep the names of the items the same), using TAB to cycle
through the string gadgets, also when you press TAB or RETURN in a gadget it
will perform tests (e.g. to see if a directory exists) and inform you if
there is a problem (recommended).

@{u}Screen Co-ordinates@{uu}

   The gadgets at the top relate to where the section name should be displayed
on the screen (the @{b}KewlCD.Menu@{ub} ANSI, which is the cursor position on
the screen. The position for the ANSI included with KewlCDPro is 26 by 4. Next is
where the currently selected section number should be displayed, the default
for this is 75 by 4.

   Next is the position of the keypress prompt (where the user selects a menu
item), this default is 16 by20. Finally is the co-ordinates of where the name
of the CD is displayed, this default is 27 by 1. (Note: It's X screen
coordinate by Y screen coordinate).

@{u}Special Directories@{uu}

   The Local directory is the directory in which the requester will default to
if you select @{b}D@{ub} from KewlCDPro's menu on a local login. Files will be copied
to this location off the CD. If you leave this blank it will default to @{b}Sys:@{ub}.

   The Temp directory is pretty special, it enables a very cool downloading
system.. Files are copied to the directory specified (on your hard disk, or
memory if ya got lots of it!) before downloading, PLUS, while downloading the
current file; the next file will be copied over at the same time! Thus saving
time on large downloads :o). Note: Files cannot be downloaded if they limit
the storage space. This must be enabled if your CD uses filenames or directory
names with spaces in, as MAX's cannot download these.

   Leave this blank if you do not wish to use this feature!

@{u}Other Configuration Options@{uu}

   The Leave message to gadget allows you to specify which user CD requests
will go to (ie. You!), when the user requests a CD, the MAX's message editor
is invoked with the name in this gadget as the "To".

   Max # of marks allows you to set the maximum number of marked files a user
can have at any one time. This can be as big as you like, it's not limited
like it is in MagicFile.

@{u}CD Modes@{uu}

   CD Mode allows you to set which mode you want to use for KewlCDPro, here is
a description of both of the modes:
   
@{u}1: Auto-detect CD@{uu}

   This will create a menu showing a list of the CDs that are available to the
   user, it will check each entry in the list to see which one is in the drive
   and tell the user what CD it found, if it found none then it will bring up
   a little message and quit, also it will not display any CDs that the user
   does not have access levels high enough to see.
   
   If you want to use this feature with 2 CD-Drives (with any more or a
   multi CD-changer it would be worth using `mode 2'), you can have two
   options in say a "CD-ROM" accessing menu, and under each entry in the menu
   you specify the DEVICE as an argument when running the door, e.g.
   Doors:KewlCD/KewlCD CD0: - this will check which CD is in CD0: and then
   look at the list of CDs and see which one it is, note you don't need the
   device argument if you only have 1 CD drive. You could have a menu like:
   
   @{b}Key:  Function:  Extra:  Lo acc:  Hi acc:  Filename/Etc:@{ub}
   1     34         0       5        10000    Doors:KewlCD/KewlCD CD0:
   2     34         0       5        10000    Doors:KewlCD/KewlCD CD1:
   
   Remember: 3 or more CD drives or a CD-Changer and you should use `mode 2'
   instead and you don't need to specify the DEVICE argument if you only have
   one drive, hey, you can even use `mode 2' for 2 drives, it's just a matter
   of preference!

@{u}2: User chooses CD@{uu}

   This will create a list as before, showing the CDs, this is meant for users
   of multiple CD drives or CD-Changers, it will give a prompt at the bottom
   and ask a user to enter the CD to access, if its not in a drive it will
   tell them that and to select another. OUT CD's are displayed RED and have
   no number next to them, and IN CD's are displayed in yellow. @{i}Registered
   users only! @{ui}

   Dual column CD list display displays twice as many sections on the screen
   for Mode 2, if you got like 40 odd CD's, you can now fit em on one screen!

   Allow archiving of lists enables a little menu to be displayed before each
   download of a list (ie. Section list, Complete list, ASCII results) which
   allows the user to select an archiving method. For more info on the
   archiving feature see the main KewlCDPro guide.

@{u}The rest!@{uu}

   The listview at the bottom contains CD Config information with the CD Config
file and access level gadgets underneith, the Up and Down move the selected
CD Config Up or Down the list, Add and Delete add new configs or Delete configs
from the list. The little cute @{b}V@{ub} pops up a requester and lets you
select a directory for that section, after you select the config it will jump
to the access gadget to let you enter an access level.
   
@{u}Menus@{uu}

   Reset       Resets the configuration items to defaults.
   Open        Open a KewlCDPro 2.0 config and edit it.
   Import      Import a configuration file from an older version of KewlCDPro,
               KewlCDPro 1.6 will import a config file from 1.6! << IMPORTANT!
   Save        Save the configuration.
   Save as     Save the configuration, ask for name of file first though.
   --------
   Keyboard Editor   Keyboard configuration editor (more below).
   --------
   About       Displays some information about the editor.
   Quit        Quits!

@{u}Keyboard Editor@{uu}

   This is for editing the KewlCDPro 2.0 @{b}Keyboard.cfg@{ub}. When you select
the Keyboard Editor you will notice an extra window open, and a little
requester asking you if it's OK to load the Keyboard.cfg (if it found one).

   Each gadget has the operation next to it, simply enter the key of your
choice into the relevant gadget and press ENTER or TAB to confirm (this will
make the editor do some checks to see if you have duplicate keys), simply enter
a @{b}-@{ub} (dash) to disable a function.

@{u}Menus@{uu}

   Reset    Resets the keys to defaults.
   Open     Opens a requester and allows you to select a Keyboard.cfg to load.
   Save     Saves the current file being edited (requester if new file).
   Save as  Saves the current file but asks for a path & name via a requester.
   --------
   Close    Quits the keyboard editor and goes back to the main editor.
 
OK.. That's your lot :o)

@ENDNODE


